author: JackHeard

description.text:
I've described models of three types of elemental carbon, "Buckyballs", "Nanotubes", and a "Diamond Lattice Model". Graphite, the most common form of carbon, remains to be done. The Naval Research Laboratory crystal site has a very nice section on carbon
http://cst-www.nrl.navy.mil/lattice/struk/carbon.html
that has information about 3 forms of graphite. Coordinates of the forms are available as well as rotatable models that can be viewed with a javascript applet. The common A9 hexagonal form appears to be the easiest to print. It's simple enough so that coordinates can be calculated with pencil and paper allowing one to position the model for the benefit of the printer. The A9 graphite structure consists of planar sheets of carbon atoms with a bond distance of 1.42 Angstroms in a hexagonal array. Alternate layers are directly above one another at a distance of 6.7 Angstroms. The intermediate layer, which is 3.35 Angstroms from the layer above and below is an identical hexagonal array, It is positioned so that a line drawn between the centers of the hexagons on the upper and lower sheets goes through a carbon atom in the intermediate layer. The fortran program, expand_graphite.f, makes the model using simple geometry and outputs openSCAD module calls. Comment statements in the program help explain how this was done. The program is a bit of a hack; it grew longer and longer as more hexagons and atoms were added. The object was to orient the sheets to be at right angles to the build surface and make it larger than the version available from the Naval Research Laboratory, I checked the finished fortran, openSCAD version against the NRL version in netfab Studio. The two versions superimposed perfectly. Two models are provided. A sturdy model, with atoms, that prints and scales well, Graphite7_x4_2c.stl. It is the output of makegraphite7.scad scaled up by a factor of 4 and with two added rings (outer diameter 44 mm, hole 30 mm, thickness 2 mm). Graphite11_x4_2c.stl is a more open model without atoms, that shows only the hexagonal lattice. The shift between the hexagonal layers can clearly be seen.

Graphite7_x4_2c.stl is about 45 by 45 by 55 mm in size.   It takes about an hour and a half to print with a raft.  Scaled down versions print well.  The picture with multiple models shows a range of sizes; the brown model in the middle foreground is Graphite7_x4_2c.stl.
The open model, Graphite11_x4_2c.stl, prints in just over an hour.  It is shown in the picture containing a single model.  Caution a bit fragile.

It should support 2,1 mm lenses quite snugly. If printed with PLA and my settings it weighs about 2.6g

description.text:
The design is inspired by the antscanada.com ant nests. Unfortunatly the shipping costs to my country are way to high, so i designed my own formicarium for my Camponotus herculeanus ants.
You can put some cotton in the base piece, stick the chamber on top of it and water the base piece from both sides (there are little holes in the walls), to regulate the humidity. The entrance blocks are for 12/16mm aquarium tubes. I separeted them, so you can design your own entrance blocks. Or if something break, you don't have to print the entire formicarium again. You need a sheet of 2mm (acrylic-) glass. I drilled a hole in the center through the glass and the formicarium to hold the sheet in place (not shown in the pictures). Alternatively, you can glue the sheet.

This is a vastly improved design of anti-vibration foot over my previous design - http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:691234.
It is partially inspired by 3DMS' tennis ball damper - http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1209709.
The solid foam-rubber balls provide total vibration isolation from the workbench and I have been using this for several months now with no loss of resilience, unlike my earlier foam 'noodle' feet. These will fit any printer with similar 5mm plate construction to the Wanhao or early Makerbots. The foam balls were 50p each from the dog-ball basket in PetsAtHome (in the UK). These were the softest of the solid rubber balls they had and are 60mm (2.36") diameter.
I designed this foot for quick printing and mine were printed using my 'swift, rough and ready' settings at 5% fill and 0.3mm layers. I'd recommend a drop of glue to attach the cups to the printer to give more stability.

Quick and easy "hook" to allow picture frames to be put on top of furniture, leaning against a wall.
Just print two FrameGrabbers and place the lower end behind the furniture and the longer on the top surface. Place the frame of the picture against the FrameGrabber and let it lean against the wall, so the small raised part in the front grab the frame.

Customizer Settings Thickness The thickness dimension defines the strength of the FrameGrabber but is mostly to control the appearance of the object. I have had good success between 3 and 5 mm. Length For creating the perfect fit for your picture frames, the most important measurement to take into consideration is the height of the frame in proportion to the lenght of the FrameGrabber.
Too short a lenght and the angle of the picture frame will be to small, increasing the risk of the picture falling over. I have so far only created for a 100 cm frame, for which the 60mm length proved sufficient. Height To change how far up the tap at the front of the FrameGrabber should reach onto the picture, the height of the object should be changed. 10-15mm seems to work fine. Depth Depth controls the part of the object that holds the picture the back of the furniture. As long as the depth is enough to prevent the picture from pulling the FrameGrabber up over the furniture your should be fine. Circ
The Circ dimension is added to give the FrameGrabber a little extra strength in the joint. To prevent the plastic from bending, the small circle brings some extra goods to the area and helps strengthen the joint. Extr
The extrusion of the part is defined here. Again this dimension is partly for aesthetically control but works fine around the 10-15mm.

description.text: Activity to easily convert your openscad design into a thingiverse customizer so that anyone can tweak around and generate their own customizations

Turn your openscad design customizable In my first activity to start using openscad http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1362201 , we learnt a few things about openscad so we are able to design things. We learnt that we had to define the parameters first, and then use the design commands.
You can share your things with the world on Thingiverse, but it would be awesome to allow more freedom to people who do not want to bother to use design tools. Well, this is really EASY to do just by adding comments on your openscad code. let's get on with it! Objectives • Become familiar with how to write in OpenScad Designing in order for Thingiverse Customizer to be able to work Audiences • Any kid studying anything in relation with 3D printing or designing student (beginners level)
• Anyone who needs a funnel fast!...but not anyone, one that noone else has Preparation • Students will need access to computers and ideally a 3D Printer in the classroom
• Computers will be equipped with the necessary 3D printing software and OpenScad.
• It is helpful to have students form into working groups of two or three so that they can collaborate on the design process. Having students work in groups is also helpful if you have a limited number of computers and/or limited 3D printer access, plus you will end up with several designs. Part 1: Complete your design on openscad Make sure that on your openscad code you put the variables definitions first and then the actual design command.
You may want to group the variables, for instance radiuses first and heights later.
Remember, variable definition could be like this:
Sides=5; Openscad variable definitions (without specific comments for customizer) Part 2: Retouch your design for customizer Now, you can just add some comments here and there for customizer to understand.
Before a block of variables you can add:
/[Funnel Settings]/
Than will create a drop down list so that you can easily group variables Before each variable, just add accomment with the text that you want to see as help on customizer this is how each variable has its comment in the line just above and this is how it looks like on customizer Step 3: Publish on Thingiverse Go to thingiverse, create a new thing, upload the openscad file, and check the box "this is a customizer" Results At the end of this project, each group of students should have:
• customised 3D printed funnels objects
• Basic familiarity with OpenScad, structured programming and thingiverse customizer

This is a stencil to help individuals draw shapes such as triangles, circles, squares, ovals, diamonds, and hexagons.

Objectives We hoped by creating this that students would be able to more easily draw shapes. Audiences This stencil would be useful to all ages. Kids can use it to help them draw, teenagers can use it in school, and adults can use it in their lives as needed. Preparation No prior knowledge is needed to use this project and it is purely to help make drawing shapes simpler. Steps 1.) We defined the problem at hand: What would be useful to a teacher or student that we could make on a 3D printer? 2.) We came up with different ideas that we thought could possibly work. 3.) We narrowed down our ideas and did research on what had already been done and what it would take to make one. 4.) We defined the criteria and constraints that would be present while making this. 5.) We looked at which ideas of ours could work. 6.) We decided our best idea was to make a stencil. 7.) We created a design proposal to give to our teacher. 8.) We created the stencil on Inventor and printed out a prototype. 9.) We looked at what had been printed out and decided what needed to be fixed. 10.) We changed what we thought was needed and resubmitted the idea. 11.) Our final draft was printed out on the 3D printer. 12.) We posted the stencil to the competition and gave it to our teacher.

I always loved the look of the J-Type Diplomatic Barge, also known as the Naboo Royal Cruiser, and thought it would be a great challenge to try and make it. I've been holding on to this one for awhile so I could release it today, to commemorate the latest release of OpenSCAD! This latest release (2011.12) is required to use these fonts, so go download it now! (http://www.openscad.org).
This is an upgrade to pipakin's OpenSCAD Font Importer, along with a bundle of generated OpenSCAD files for the fonts from the Google Web Font directory (http://www.google.com/webfonts). As noted on the original, there is a significant bug (not known whether the bug is in the font importer or in OpenSCAD itself) causing varying levels of font support. I rendered a sentence in each one to determine the level of support as best I can. My research was not exhaustive and some entries in the table below will be wrong. That said, I tried to be as accurate as I could and if you notice anything wrong/missing please let me know and I will correct it.
If I said it is supported, that means I was unable to find any problems with rendering the font. â€œPartialâ€ means it seems to work with the exception of some letters (noted in the â€œNotesâ€ column). â€œNoâ€ means I was unable to render a simple sentence with the font, usually due to a 2-manifold error. There are a number of improvements over the original:
  • Use a normal string as input (up to 100 characters)
  • Use the "extra" parameter to add extra space between characters
  • Use the "height" parameter to specify the extruded height
  • Specify height=0 to keep the text 2D for .dxf export
  • BezConic module inside each file so you only need to include the font file
    • Get the latest code from here: https://github.com/brad/OpenSCAD-Font-Importer ALSO NOTE: These font files are not meant to be edited, or even viewed. If you have a weak heart, or are pregnant, do not look inside because there be dragons. Don't say I didn't warn you!

This Baymax was started as I was modeling how to use the TinkerCad software. The movie, Big Hero 6, had been released earlier that year so I was trying to make it relative to the students for engagement purposes. Once I started modeling for a class, I would erase it all and start over the next class, however, I started thinking that it would be cool to see it completed. While the students were working on their robots I was working on Baymax. This also allowed students to observe as I worked, and ask questions on how I created a certain shape. This was a great subject because I used many different geometrical shapes, and had to figure out which shapes would be best used to cut other shapes.

Printer Brand:

MakerBot

Printer:

MakerBot Replicator 2

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

Standard

Infill:

10%

I used TinkerCad.com to create this model. I usually teach my students basics of the program, and how to get around the interface. 
Start- I started with cylinder shapes to create the torso, and egg shapes for the pecks. I didn't resize them proportionally all the time, only because there are some parts of the body that are oddly shaped. 
For the helmet, I used a sphere to start, and I cut out the eye section with a rectangle. I had to place a smaller sphere in the helmet to show his head. I then too a hexagon and stretched it a little for the mouth area of the mask and to make it look more attached I added wedges on both sides coming out from the helmet. 
The wings were very difficult. I used wedge shapes, rectangles, and custom curved shapes to create the curves on the wings.

Objectives: The student will be expected to create a 3d object by thinking critically and using problem solving skills. They will be able to plan, manage, and make informed decisions about which geometrical shapes to use to create the form they want. They will also be able to understand new technology and how it operates.
Audiences: I teach this project in high school, grades 9-11. This project would be their 3rd small project with the program, so I would say a novice skill level.
Preparation: I usually show students some keyboard shortcuts to view their objects at 360 degrees, Then I take them through the tutorials provided by the website. They need to understand the 3d platform, and how the shapes can work together to create the forms they want.
Steps: After all the preparation, I tell the students to find a cartoon or animated character they like; one with more of a geometric look/shape. When they come in to class the next day, we begin. I start with a more general character, so students can understand how and where to start on their own. I do a couple of cut-outs with the shapes to make sure they know how it works, and I let them work on their selection. As they work, I begin to walk around to answer questions. If there is a common question, or one that I feel is essential, then I refer back to my tutorial so all the students can see. Some students choose to just do a boxed figure, but that's when we have to encourage them to do something bigger and better. It is when the students are encouraged that they learn more, because they enjoy a challenge and become excited when they see the final outcome.

This is my second attempt at a soprano ukulele. It has a louder much fuller tone. This design can be printed on a minimum 5 x 8 printer platform without supports. I used PLA and the structure is very sturdy. The neck is connected to the body (lower hole) with 1/4-20 x 1-1/2 L socket head cap screws, washers, and nuts. The upper hole has a 1/4-20 x 3 L pan head screw for neck strength. The hole inserts included with my other ukulele will also work with this one. Pick one and snap it into the hole in the fretboard bottom. You will need to place the two pieces on a flat surface and smack them together for a snap fit. The ukulele fretboards and bottom flange are attached with #6 x 1/2 L flat head wood screws. The fretboard bottom and bottom flange are the structural pieces that hold the body halves together. There will be a tiny gap when the project is finished. You can fill it with epoxy if you want but it isn't necessary. The pegs are standard friction type pegs. The strings are fed through curved holes at the top of the fretboard and are twist wrapped. The bridge is loose and should be glued or adhered into the slot provided. This will keep it from shifting which may cause a snapping sound.when played. If you have a problem installing the 1/4-20 nuts & washers you can epoxy them in-line with the hole leaving the threads clear for the screws. Also the plastic will eventually relax under tension and lose tuning. You can speed this up by warming the ukulele slightly for a few minutes near a fireplace, cooling to room temp and re-tuning. Update 1/8/2018
  • Added various Bridge heights to customize action (3 different heights included)
  • Modified Fretboard Bottom posts into a captive block for string tension
  • Eliminated frets 15 thru 18 since they didn't function properly
  • Lowered Fretboard Bottom top surface forward of the sound hole
  • Added a Large Hole insert with a skirt to increase sound output and cover body flaws.
    This may be a bit difficult to install since the skirt protrudes inward

Simple trekking pole holder that can go on a strap for a molle bag or any other bag with straps.
You may need to put poles in facing opposite directions (like in photo) to accommodate baskets.
Works well with my REI poles, openscad file should be pretty easy to modify for any set of poles.
I printed two so I could keep the poles steady on my bag.
